05470nam a22006975i 9780226697864DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021040707  a9780226697864  a(DE-B1597)626066  a(OCoLC)1314613227  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aE185.97.S86bN63 2022 4aE185.97.S86bN63 2022 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a974.9/65aB2231 aNobles, Gregory, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Education of Betsey Stockton :bAn Odyssey of Slavery and Freedom /cGregory Nobles. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- t1 Given, as a Slave -- t2 She Calls Herself Betsey Stockton -- t3 A Long Adieu -- t4 A Missionary’s Life Is Very Laborious -- t5 Philadelphia’s First “Coloured Infant School” -- t6 From Ashes to Assertion -- t7 Betsey Stockton’s Princeton Education -- t8 A Time of War, a Final Peace -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA perceptive and inspiring biography of an extraordinary woman born into slavery who, through grit and determination, became a historic social and educational leader. The life of Betsey Stockton (ca. 1798–1865) is a remarkable story of a Black woman’s journey from slavery to emancipation, from antebellum New Jersey to the Hawai‘ian Islands, and from her own self-education to a lifetime of teaching others—all told against the backdrop of the early United States’ pervasive racism. It’s a compelling chronicle of a critical time in American history and a testament to the courage and commitment of a woman whose persistence grew into a potent form of resistance. When Betsey Stockton was a child, she was “given, as a slave” to the household of Rev. Ashbel Green, a prominent pastor and later the president of what is now Princeton University. Although she never went to school, she devoured the books in Green’s library. After being emancipated, she used that education to benefit other people of color, first in Hawai‘i as a missionary, then Philadelphia, and, for the last three decades of her life, Princeton—a college town with a genteel veneer that never fully hid its racial hostility. Betsey Stockton became a revered figure in Princeton’s sizeable Black population, a founder of religious and educational institutions, and a leader engaged in the day-to-day business of building communities. In this first book-length telling of Betsey Stockton’s story, Gregory Nobles illuminates both a woman and her world, following her around the globe, and showing how a determined individual could challenge her society’s racial obstacles from the ground up. It’s at once a revealing lesson on the struggles of Stockton’s times and a fresh inspiration for our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican American womenzNew JerseyzPrincetonvBiography. 0aFreed personszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aFreedmenzUnited StatesvBiography. 0aMissionarieszHawaiivBiography. 0aMissionarieszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPresbyteriansvBiography. 0aSlaveszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen missionarieszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen teacherszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aBetsey Johnson, Princeton, Hawaii, people of color, antebellum America, slavery, racism, resistance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruy